Set up one persistent Node context module and reuse it:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: {
    type: "persistent",
    dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data",
  },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Important constraints:
- Install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency for Node backends.
- Do **not** create a new context per request.
- Call `await jazz.shutdown()` on process exit (and handle SIGTERM/SIGINT).
- `persistent` driver stores local durable state; `memory` driver is ephemeral and requires `serverUrl` for durability.
- `BACKEND_SECRET` is required for `asBackend/forRequest/forSession/withAttribution*` on a server-connected setup; keep secrets server-only (no public env exposure).
- Wait for durability tier explicitly on endpoints that must return after durable replication/write visibility (e.g., `wait({ tier: "edge" })` where needed).

Use `null` for nullable columns. In Jazz, `undefined` is treated as "leave unchanged," so the `projectId` won’t clear.

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todo.id, {
  projectId: null,
});
```
That clears the optional relation field.

Use query accessors so the subscription tracks reactive inputs.

```ts
// Svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
  import { app } from "./schema";

  const done = $state(false);
  const search = $state("");

  const sub = new QuerySubscription(() =>
    app.todos
      .where({ done, title: { contains: search } })
      .orderBy("title", "asc")
  );
</script>

<div>
  {#if sub.loading}<p>Loading…</p>{/if}
  {#if sub.error}<p>{sub.error.message}</p>{/if}
  {#if sub.current} ... {#each sub.current as todo} ... {/each} {/if}
</div>
```

```tsx
// Solid
const [done, setDone] = createSignal(false);
const [search, setSearch] = createSignal("");

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos
    .where({ done: done(), title: { contains: search() } })
    .orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```
Both forms re-run when `done`/`search` changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two independent writes that should appear together in local-first UI but don’t need atomic authority-level acceptance.

Use `db.transaction(...)` for two writes that must be validated together and only become authoritative globally as one unit.

```ts
// optimistic, independent local visibility
const batch = db.batch((b) => {
  b.insert(app.todos, { title: "A", done: false });
  b.insert(app.todos, { title: "B", done: false });
});
await batch.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

```ts
// atomic, authority-bound, all-or-nothing global visibility
const tx = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.insert(app.todos, { title: "A", done: false });
  tx.insert(app.todos, { title: "B", done: false });
});
await tx.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Upload flow (edge-complete success):

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, {
  name: blob.name,
  mimeType: blob.type || 'application/octet-stream',
  tier: 'edge',
});

const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label: 'avatar',
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: 'edge' });
```

The `tier: 'edge'` on both calls makes success mean helper inserts and parent row are durably visible at edge.

Download flow with incomplete local state handling:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: 'local' });
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    // file metadata missing/unreadable
  } else if (err instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    // local is incomplete: retry at stronger tier
    const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: 'edge' });
  } else {
    throw err;
  }
}
```

- `FileNotFoundError`: no visible file row.
- `IncompleteFileDataError`: metadata/parts incomplete (`invalid-file-record`, `missing-part`, `part-size-mismatch`); do not assume read will self-heal.
- Use stronger tier read (`edge`) for completion guarantee, and surface explicit “sync in progress/retry” state when incomplete.

Delete in dependency order so inherited delete permissions stay valid while removing file data:

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: 'edge' });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: 'edge' });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Never delete `uploads` first, because file/part delete rights are usually inherited from the parent row reference and can disappear when the parent is gone. Keep deletion in this order: **part rows → file row → parent row**.

Use `SchemaBuilder` + `TableSchema::builder` for schema, `JazzClient` for transport, and a single strict decoder per projection.

1) Define projection schema once:
```rust
let query = QueryBuilder::new("todos")
  .select(["id", "title", "done", "description"])
  .build();
```

2) Decode centrally with a strict positional parser:
```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct TodoRow { id: ObjectId, title: String, done: bool, description: Option<String> }

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if values.len() != 4 { return Err(AppError::Decode("unexpected projection width".into())); }
    let title = match &values[0] { Value::Text(s) => s.clone(), _ => return Err(AppError::Decode("title must be text".into())) };
    let done = match values[1] { Value::Boolean(v) => v, _ => return Err(AppError::Decode("done must be bool".into())) };
    let description = match &values[2] {
        Value::Null => None,
        Value::Text(s) => Some(s.clone()),
        _ => return Err(AppError::Decode("description must be text|null".into())),
    };
    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}
```

3) Query/write through public API:
- `query` -> `Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)>`
- map every row via `decode_todo`
- inserts use `row_input!(...)`
```rust
let (_id, _values, batch) = client.insert("todos", row_input!("title"=>"Ship", "done"=>false, "description"=>Value::Null))?;
let batch_id = client.update(id, vec![("done".into(), Value::Boolean(true))])?;
```

4) For services that need caller provenance/ordering, request explicit columns and keep decoder/tested projection order coupled so schema drift fails fast.

Use a real local server + two clients, then assert convergence via stable sets (not array order). Example:

```ts
import { createDb } from "jazz-tools";
import { expect, it, vi } from "vitest";
import { startLocalJazzServer, } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { app } from "../schema";

it("syncs multiple rows deterministically regardless of result order", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  let alice: any;
  let bob: any;

  try {
    alice = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, driver: { type: "memory" } });
    bob = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, driver: { type: "memory" } });

    const created = [
      await alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "A", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      await alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "B", done: true }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      await alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "C", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    ];

    const expected = new Set(created.map((r) => r.id));

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
      const got = new Set(rows.map((r) => r.id));
      expect(Array.from(got).sort()).toEqual(Array.from(expected).sort());
    });
  } finally {
    await alice?.shutdown();
    await bob?.shutdown();
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

Why stable: row presence/values are checked via ID set (order-insensitive) and edge-tier waits prevent timing assumptions.

Use session-scoped policy tests; verify Bob cannot read Alice’s row and cannot mutate it, while Alice can.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

describe("row access policy", () => {
  it("denies Bob both read and write access to Alice-owned row", async () => {
    const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
    const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

    const todo = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "private" }).value;

    // Read policy: denied reads should be absent, not throw.
    await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

    // Write policy: denied mutation.
    bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "hacked" }));

    // Optional sanity: Alice can mutate.
    alice.expectAllowed((db) => db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "owner" }));
  });
});
```

Use `createPolicyTestApp` for this kind of unit-level policy check; it keeps assertions black-boxed and local-first behavior explicit.
